Wat led to the Revolution of Dignity? Cite if possible

The Revolution of Dignity, also known as Euromaidan, was a series of events in Ukraine that led to significant political changes in the country. It took place in 2013-2014 as a response to the government's decision to suspend an association agreement with the European Union. The protests were fueled by widespread frustration over corruption, human rights abuses, and the government's ties to Russia. The movement eventually grew into a massive demonstration demanding political reform and closer ties with Europe.

The Revolution of Dignity culminated in the ousting of then-President Viktor Yanukovych in February 2014. This revolution set the stage for subsequent events, including the Russo-Ukrainian War and the ongoing conflict in the region.

(Source: [Wikipedia - Euromaidan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Ukrainian_War))
Wat led to the Revolution of Dignity? Cite if possible

The Revolution of Dignity, also known as the Maidan Revolution or the Ukrainian Revolution, took place in Ukraine in February 2014. It was a culmination of the Euromaidan protests that started in November 2013. The revolution was triggered by President Viktor Yanukovych's decision not to sign a political association and free trade agreement with the European Union, opting for closer ties to Russia instead. The deadly clashes between protesters and state forces in Kyiv led to the ousting of Yanukovych, the reinstatement of the 2004 Constitution of Ukraine, and the beginning of the 2014 Russo-Ukrainian War.

Source: [Wikipedia - Revolution of Dignity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolution_of_Dignity)
